<subSubSection box="[151,850,1770,1797]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,850,1770,1797]" box="[151,850,1770,1797]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,850,1770,1797]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Subtribe 
<taxonomicName authority="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" box="[268,713,1770,1796]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Hammatoferina">Hammatoferina Cadena-Castañeda</taxonomicName>
n. subtrib.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1840,2041]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1840,1866]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Medium-sized (total length 
<quantity box="[607,733,1840,1867]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.25" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" unit="mm" value="52.5" valueMax="55.0" valueMin="50.0">50–55 mm</quantity>
) and slender (
<figureCitation box="[902,1011,1840,1867]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1607,1631]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,180,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-21@24.[163,1424,180,1585]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 15. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838) male. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C and D. Head and thorax in dorsal and lateral view respectively. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in dorsal view (draw from H. brasiliensis n. syn., by Piza 1980)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876249/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 15A</figureCitation>
). Head ovoid in frontal view, vertex compressed and acuminate (
<figureCitation box="[467,568,1874,1901]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1607,1631]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,180,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-21@24.[163,1424,180,1585]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 15. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838) male. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C and D. Head and thorax in dorsal and lateral view respectively. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in dorsal view (draw from H. brasiliensis n. syn., by Piza 1980)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876249/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 15B</figureCitation>
), antennae with groups of setae along the flagellum (
<figureCitation box="[1159,1307,1874,1901]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1607,1631]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,180,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-21@24.[163,1424,180,1585]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 15. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838) male. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C and D. Head and thorax in dorsal and lateral view respectively. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in dorsal view (draw from H. brasiliensis n. syn., by Piza 1980)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876249/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Figs. 15C–D</figureCitation>
). Pronotum smooth and unmodified (
<figureCitation box="[431,579,1909,1936]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1607,1631]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,180,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-21@24.[163,1424,180,1585]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 15. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838) male. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C and D. Head and thorax in dorsal and lateral view respectively. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in dorsal view (draw from H. brasiliensis n. syn., by Piza 1980)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876249/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Figs. 15C–D</figureCitation>
), margin of lateral lobes rounded and slightly thickened (
<figureCitation box="[1216,1320,1909,1936]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1607,1631]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,180,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-21@24.[163,1424,180,1585]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 15. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838) male. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C and D. Head and thorax in dorsal and lateral view respectively. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in dorsal view (draw from H. brasiliensis n. syn., by Piza 1980)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876249/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 15D</figureCitation>
). Tegmina lanceolate, about five times as long as wide. MA vein extending along for two thirds of the tegmen length (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1607,1631]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,180,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-21@24.[163,1424,180,1585]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 15. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838) male. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C and D. Head and thorax in dorsal and lateral view respectively. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in dorsal view (draw from H. brasiliensis n. syn., by Piza 1980)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876249/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 15A</figureCitation>
). Hind femora armed with small triangular spines on the ventral margin. Male cerci robust and forked, gripper in shape (
<figureCitation box="[259,360,2014,2041]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1607,1631]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,180,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-21@24.[163,1424,180,1585]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 15. Hammatofera nodicornis (Burmeister, 1838) male. A. Habitus in lateral view. B. Frons. C and D. Head and thorax in dorsal and lateral view respectively. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in dorsal view (draw from H. brasiliensis n. syn., by Piza 1980)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876249/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 15E</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor twice as long as the pronotum, sharply upcurved, with rounded tip.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,855,151,177]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,537]" box="[199,855,151,177]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,340,151,177]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,151,177]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Type</typeStatus>
genus.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" box="[347,851,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Hammatofera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[347,503,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Hammatofera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C." box="[510,851,151,177]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref38497" refString="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C. (1878) Monographie der Phaneropteriden, F. A. Brockhaus, Wien, 401 pp., pls. 1 - 8." type="book chapter" year="1878">Brunner von Wattenwyl, 1878</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,537]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,186,212]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,432,187,213]" name="Brazil" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: Atlantic coast, Atlantic Forest of the Caatinga biogeographic province, 
<collectingRegion box="[1232,1308,187,213]" country="Brazil" name="Parana" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Paraná</collectingRegion>
forests and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,407,223,249]" class="Pinopsida" family="Araucariaceae" genus="Araucaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angustifolia">
<emphasis box="[151,407,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Araucaria angustifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forest (according to the classification by 
<bibRefCitation author="Morrone, J. J." box="[871,1036,223,249]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 148" refId="ref41742" refString="Morrone, J. J. (2001) Biogeografia de America Latina y el Caribe. M &amp; T - Manuales &amp; Tesis SEA, Zaragoza, 3, 1 - 148." type="journal article" year="2001">Morrone 2001</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingRegion box="[1056,1121,223,249]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Bahia</collectingRegion>
to 
<collectingRegion box="[1157,1321,223,249]" country="Brazil" name="Santa Catarina" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Santa Catarina</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[1335,1408,223,249]" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="26.[151,202,901,925]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,215,858]" captionTargetId="figure-21@26.[151,1436,215,858]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Map 1. Distribution map of Hammatofera nodicornis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6885555" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6885555/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Map 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,537]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,258,284]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Comments.</emphasis>
This is a unique member of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rehn" authorityYear="1950" box="[687,797,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Dysoniini">Dysoniini</taxonomicName>
distinguished by phyllomorphic camouflage. The general habitus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" box="[273,429,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Hammatofera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[273,429,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Hammatofera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, along with ovipositor shape in females, resembles in appearance members of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Braun &amp; García, 2022" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Braun &amp; García" authorityYear="2022" box="[1334,1437,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" status="n. subtrib." subTribe="Markiina">Markiina</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,277,330,357]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,277,330,357]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="subTribe">n. subtrib.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
The main difference is the lack of lichen camouflage shown by that subtribe: no pale coloration, nor modifications of vertex or pronotum, and absence of long spines on femora, genicular lobes, and tibiae. Based on comparison with new specimens, 
<taxonomicName authority="Piza, 1980" authorityName="Piza" authorityYear="1980" box="[526,812,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Hammatofera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis" status="n. syn.">
<emphasis box="[526,688,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">H. brasiliensis</emphasis>
Piza, 1980
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[818,894,403,429]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[818,894,403,429]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">n. syn.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, is found to be the same species as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Burmeister, 1838)" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1838" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Hammatofera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nodicornis">
<emphasis box="[1283,1436,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">H. nodicornis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Burmeister, H." box="[159,357,439,465]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="397 - 756" refId="ref38528" refString="Burmeister, H. (1838) Kaukerfe, Gymnognatha (Erste Halfte: Vulgo Orthoptera). Handbuch der Entomologie, Series 2, 2 (I - VIII), 397 - 756." type="journal article" year="1838">Burmeister, 1838</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Male cerci and subgenital plate are similar, and shape of ovipositor and female subgenital plate present at most intraspecific variation. Therefore, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" box="[717,873,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Hammatofera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[717,873,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Hammatofera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains monotypic, and this subtribe so far comprises a single species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,769,618,645]" box="[151,769,618,645]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,769,618,645]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Subtribe 
<taxonomicName authority="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" box="[268,632,618,644]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Markiina">Markiina Cadena-Castañeda</taxonomicName>
n. subtrib.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,690,1473]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,690,716]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small to medium-sized (
<quantity box="[568,697,690,717]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.75" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="47.5" valueMax="65.0" valueMin="30.0">30–65 mm</quantity>
), slender insects, background coloration dark green, with bright greenish white or yellowish green filamentous markings all over the body, general appearance usually whitish and often spiny. Head longer than wide in frontal view; vertex elevated as a cone or a spine (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" box="[1184,1290,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Machima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1184,1290,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Machima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only weakly elevated); antennae filiform, unmodified. Pronotum smooth, with stripes that in some groups vary according to species, anterior and posterior margin of the pronotal disc with a spine or without (both spines are present in all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="White" authorityYear="1862" box="[180,262,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Markia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[180,262,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Markia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as well as 
<emphasis box="[381,756,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2013" box="[381,660,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lichenodraculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holgeri">Lichenodraculus holgeri</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Braun" authorityYear="2011" box="[669,756,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lichenodraculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matti">L. matti</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
has only one spine on the anterior margin), rarely with an laterally expanded metazona (only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rehn" authorityYear="1950" box="[514,635,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Apolinaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[514,635,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Apolinaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). At rest tegmina with costal margin broadly curved upward throughout the entire length, and the anal margin being almost straight or slightly concave, with the apex curved upward (giving an overall undulate appearance), tip broadly truncate. The anal margin has pyramidal, sclerotized sensilla. Genicular lobes with a well-developed and usually long spine, spines of femora and tibiae elongated and pointed. Hind margin of abdominal tergites with spines. Male cerci variable in shape, external branch usually as long as inner branch or only slightly longer (the species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" box="[543,649,1087,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Machima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[543,649,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Machima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are special in presenting a very long and thin external branch, with the internal branch reduced to a small spine). Subgenital plate unmodified. Ovipositor twice as long as the pronotum or a little longer, valves only a little broadened and slightly serrulate, curving upward; female cerci thin and moderately elongated (in some 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Braun" authorityYear="2011" box="[371,559,1195,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Lichenodraculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[371,559,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Lichenodraculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females almost as long as the ovipositor).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,582,1231,1257]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,690,1473]" box="[199,582,1231,1257]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,340,1231,1257]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,1231,1257]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Type</typeStatus>
genus.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="White, 1862" authorityName="White" authorityYear="1862" box="[347,578,1231,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Markia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[347,429,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Markia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="White, A." box="[436,578,1231,1257]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="175 - 284" refId="ref43428" refString="White, A. (1862) Class V - Insects (Insecta). Richardson's Museum of Natural History. 2, 175 - 284." type="journal article" year="1862">White, 1862</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,690,1473]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1266,1292]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Distribution.</emphasis>
From the southwest of 
<collectingCountry box="[621,707,1267,1293]" name="Mexico" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Mexico</collectingCountry>
to southern 
<collectingCountry box="[848,920,1267,1293]" name="Brazil" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. Most species are found in the Andean region between 
<collectingCountry box="[251,366,1303,1329]" name="Venezuela" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[420,502,1303,1329]" name="Bolivia" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J." box="[517,807,1303,1329]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="101 - 123" refId="ref38781" refString="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. (2013 b) La tribu Dysoniini parte III: Adiciones a los generos Apolinaria, Lichenodraculus, Machimoides y Markia (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae). Journal of Orthoptera Research, 22 (2), 101 - 123. https: // doi. org / 10.1665 / 034.022.0202" type="journal article" year="2013">Cadena-Castañeda 2013b</bibRefCitation>
, c).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,690,1473]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1338,1364]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Comments.</emphasis>
Most genera of this subtribe were formerly included in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="White" authorityYear="1862" box="[1055,1137,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Markia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1055,1137,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Markia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus group by CadenaCastañeda, 2013b. The species show lichenomorphic camouflage, specialized on fruticose or arbuscular lichens such as 
<taxonomicName box="[244,316,1411,1436]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Parmeliaceae" genus="Usnea" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[244,316,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Usnea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Diagnoses of the genera are provided, omitting the common characters already described for the subtribe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
